    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>NAP consistency</strong> is the practice of ensuring your business Name, Address, and Phone number are formatted identically across every online directory, website, and platform. Google uses NAP data to verify business legitimacy. Inconsistencies — even minor ones like "St" vs "Street" — cause Google to treat listings as separate entities, splitting ranking signals and suppressing local pack visibility.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2.3x local pack lift</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Audit frequency</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Quarterly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local businesses lose rankings not from bad content or weak backlinks — but from a phone number formatted differently across six directories. NAP consistency is the unsexy foundational work that separates businesses that show up in the local pack from those that don't.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is NAP consistency?</h2>
        <p>NAP stands for Name, Address, and Phone number — the three pieces of contact information that appear across your Google Business Profile, website, Yelp, Facebook, Apple Maps, and dozens of industry directories. Consistency means every instance uses exactly the same format, character for character.</p>
        <p>Google's local algorithm cross-references NAP data across citations to confirm your business is real, located where you claim, and reachable at the number you list. When it finds contradictions, it loses confidence — and lower-confidence businesses rank lower.</p>
        <p>Common inconsistencies that trigger this problem:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Name variations</strong>: "Joe's Plumbing" vs "Joe's Plumbing LLC" vs "Joes Plumbing"</li>
          <li><strong>Address formatting</strong>: "123 Main Street" vs "123 Main St" vs "123 Main St." vs "123 Main Street, Suite 4" vs "123 Main St #4"</li>
          <li><strong>Phone formatting</strong>: "(555) 123-4567" vs "555-123-4567" vs "5551234567" vs "+1 555 123 4567"</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's trust signal</div>
          <p>Moz's Local Search Ranking Factors research found that <strong>businesses with consistent NAP across 50+ directories rank 2.3x higher in the local pack</strong> than businesses with inconsistent NAP. A single inconsistent phone number across 10 directories can reduce local pack visibility by 15-30%.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why NAP consistency matters for local SEO</h2>
        <p>Local SEO runs on trust signals. Google decides which businesses to show in the local pack — the map-based results that capture 44% of all local search clicks — based on three factors: relevance, distance, and prominence. NAP consistency directly affects all three by reinforcing your entity's identity in Google's Knowledge Graph.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Entity verification.</strong> Google treats your business as a single "entity" in its Knowledge Graph. Clean, matching NAP across sources makes the entity clearer and stronger. Inconsistent NAP creates ambiguity — Google may index your business as two or three separate entities, fragmenting your ranking signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Citation authority.</strong> Citations (directory mentions of your NAP) act like local backlinks. Each consistent citation sends a trust signal. Inconsistent citations cancel each other out — the signal noise tells Google "this business's information is unreliable."</li>
          <li><strong>Consumer trust.</strong> BrightLocal data shows 73% of consumers lose trust in a business when they find inconsistent contact information. Customers who call a disconnected number or drive to a wrong address leave one-star reviews, which compound the damage.</li>
          <li><strong>Data aggregator propagation.</strong> Data aggregators — Neustar, Infogroup, Acxiom — scrape and distribute business information to hundreds of directories. If they pick up a wrong address, it propagates everywhere within weeks, creating a problem that takes months to undo.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How NAP consistency works as a ranking signal</h2>
        <p>Google's local ranking system functions like a voting mechanism. Each directory listing that matches your canonical NAP casts a "vote" confirming your business identity. The more votes, the more confident Google is — and confident businesses rank higher.</p>
        <p>The process works in three stages:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Stage 1: Google crawls your citations</span><br>
          Google Business Profile: <span class="uf-new">Joe's Plumbing · 123 Main St · (555) 123-4567</span><br>
          Yelp: <span class="uf-new">Joe's Plumbing · 123 Main St · (555) 123-4567</span> <span class="uf-status">✓ Match</span><br>
          Facebook: <span class="uf-old">Joes Plumbing · 123 Main Street · 555-123-4567</span> <span class="uf-comment">✗ 3 mismatches</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Stage 2: Google scores entity confidence</span><br>
          Matching citations: <span class="uf-new">28</span> / Total citations: <span class="uf-label">41</span><br>
          Entity confidence score: <span class="uf-status">68%</span> <span class="uf-comment">(below 80% threshold)</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Stage 3: Ranking impact</span><br>
          Local pack position: <span class="uf-old">5th</span> vs competitor at 95% confidence: <span class="uf-new">1st</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Types of NAP inconsistencies — which hurt most</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Inconsistency type</th><th>Example</th><th>SEO impact</th><th>Frequency</th></tr>
            </thead>
