                <td class="cell-meh">Medium — address entity split</td>
                <td>Common</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Phone format</strong></td>
                <td>"(555) 123" vs "555-123" vs "+1-555"</td>
                <td class="cell-meh">Medium — phone entity mismatch</td>
                <td>Common</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Tracking number on citation</strong></td>
                <td>Campaign number on Yelp listing</td>
                <td class="cell-no">High — different number altogether</td>
                <td>Less common but severe</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Old address still live</strong></td>
                <td>Previous location on 40+ directories</td>
                <td class="cell-no">Very high — factual contradiction</td>
                <td>Common after moves</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real NAP consistency examples</h2>
        <p>Here is what good and bad NAP consistency looks like in practice, with the downstream ranking impact.</p>

        <h3>Example 1: The law firm with a duplicate entity</h3>
        <p>A personal injury firm in Austin operated as "Smith &amp; Associates Law Firm" on their website but was listed as "Smith Associates" on Yelp, "Smith and Associates" on Avvo, and "Smith &amp; Associates" on Google Business Profile. Three Google entities existed for the same firm. After standardizing to "Smith &amp; Associates Law Firm" across 47 directories over 90 days, their local pack ranking for "personal injury lawyer Austin" moved from position 6 to position 2.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: The restaurant that moved and forgot</h3>
        <p>A Thai restaurant relocated three blocks in 2023. They updated Google Business Profile immediately but left 34 other directory listings showing the old address. Google's local algorithm detected a conflict between the GBP address and widespread citation data. The restaurant's local pack visibility dropped 40% within two months of the move. The fix — updating all 34 citations — took six weeks but recovered rankings within four months.</p>

        <h3>Example 3: Call tracking number contamination</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company installed a call tracking number across their Yelp and Yellow Pages listings for campaign attribution. Google saw three different phone numbers (tracking + local + toll-free) across their citation profile. NAP confidence dropped and their local pack ranking for "HVAC repair near me" fell from 3rd to 8th. Removing tracking numbers from citations and standardizing to one local number recovered positions within 60 days.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">NAP consistency vs citation building — which to do first</h2>
        <p>A common mistake: building new citations before fixing existing inconsistencies. New citations add volume but amplify the noise if your existing NAP is inconsistent.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Fix NAP first when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have existing citations with variations</li>
              <li>You recently moved or changed your number</li>
              <li>Your local pack ranking dropped suddenly</li>
              <li>You've changed business names</li>
              <li>A NAP audit reveals 20%+ inconsistency rate</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Build new citations when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Existing NAP is clean and consistent</li>
              <li>You have fewer than 30 directory listings</li>
              <li>Competitors have significantly more citations</li>
              <li>You're launching in a new market</li>
              <li>Industry-specific directories are unclaimed</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for NAP consistency</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Choose one canonical NAP format and document it.</strong> Write it down exactly — including punctuation — and share it with every employee, agency, and contractor who touches directory listings. Treat it as a style guide rule.</li>
          <li><strong>Use USPS-standard address formatting.</strong> Run your address through the USPS address verification tool to get the official formatted version. Use that as your canonical format everywhere.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix data aggregators first.</strong> Neustar/Localeze, Infogroup/Data Axle, Acxiom, and Foursquare push NAP to hundreds of directories. Correcting them at the source prevents downstream drift.</li>
          <li><strong>Never use call tracking numbers in directory citations.</strong> Create a separate tracking number for paid ads only. Your primary local number goes in every citation — no exceptions.</li>
          <li><strong>Run a quarterly NAP audit.</strong> Directories get scraped, merged, and updated by third parties. Set a calendar reminder every 90 days to check your top 20 citations for drift.</li>
          <li><strong>Add LocalBusiness schema to your website.</strong> Implement JSON-LD schema markup on your contact page and footer with your canonical NAP. This gives Google a machine-readable authoritative source to cross-reference against all citations.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — updating GBP but not citations</div>
          <p>When you move or change your phone number, Google Business Profile is the first thing businesses update. It is also the only thing many businesses update. The result: GBP shows the new address while 40+ directories still show the old one. Google sees a conflict and reduces confidence in your local listing. Always treat a NAP change as a full citation audit task, not a one-field update.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common NAP consistency mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Creating duplicate GBP listings</strong> — two Google Business Profiles for the same location split reviews and NAP signals. Claim and merge them.</li>
          <li><strong>Abbreviating inconsistently</strong> — using "Ave" in some listings and "Avenue" in others. Pick one and apply it everywhere.</li>
          <li><strong>Using P.O. boxes on local citations</strong> — Google requires a physical street address for local pack eligibility. P.O. boxes disqualify you.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring industry-specific directories</strong> — a dentist on Healthgrades with a different address than Google Business Profile sends a contradiction to an authoritative source Google trusts.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping Apple Business Connect</strong> — Apple Maps is the default on iPhones. An inconsistent Apple listing affects 57% of smartphone users who use Apple's default browser and maps.</li>
        </ul>

